{
  "style": "IEEE",
  "texts": [
    "The chromatic number of a graph is the smallest k such that the graph is k-colorable and denoted by χ(G).If G = K n, its chromatic number is χ(K n) = n. If G 1 = (V 1, E 1) and G 2 = (V 2, E 2) are vertex-disjoint graphs (V 1 ∩ V 2 = ∅), their graph sum is G 1 + G 2 = (V 1 ∪ V 2, E 1 ∪ E 2).",
    "The join operation between two graphs, G 1 ∨ G 2, is the graph obtained from G 1 + G 2 by adding new edges between each vertex of G 1 and all vertices of G 2.",
    "Given a graph G and a positive integer d, the d-power of G = (V, E) is the graph G d = (V, E ′)such that two vertices are adjacent in G d if and only if the distance between them in G is at most d. In this work, we will frequently use the graphs K k-1 ∨ P n-k+1 and P k n, the latter called k-ribbon in [15].",
    "For instance, the graph K 1 ∨ P n-1 is called a fan of order n, and the graph P 2 n is called a 2-ribbon of order n. A graph G = (V, E) is chordal if every cycle of size greater than or equal to 4 admits a chord (that is, an edge whose endpoints are non-consecutive vertices in the cycle).",
    "A subset S ⊂ V is a vertex separator for a pair of non-adjacent vertices u and v (a uv-separator) if removing S from the graph separates u and v into distinct connected components."
  ],
  "correct_citations": [
    "Given a graph G and a positive integer d, the d-power of G = (V, E) is the graph G d = (V, E ′)such that two vertices are adjacent in G d if and only if the distance between them in G is at most d. In this work, we will frequently use the graphs K k-1 ∨ P n-k+1 and P k n, the latter called k-ribbon in [15]."
